======================================================================
PART 4: b0 sign at n=5 vs a1
======================================================================
  b0 = 1 - a1 (at n=5, since a2=0)
  b0 <= 0 iff a1 >= 1 iff tournament has at least one directed 3-cycle
  b0 > 0 iff a1 = 0 iff tournament is transitive
  # transitive n=5: 120/1024

  Transitive iff a1=0 iff acyclic (for tournaments)
  At n=7: transitive tournament exists, has b0=1 > 0
  Random sampling missed it because P(transitive) = 7!/2^21 = 5040/2097152 ~ 0.0024

  Expected # transitive tournaments at n=7:
    n! = 5040
    2^C(n,2) = 2097152
    P(transitive) = 5040/2097152 = 0.002403

======================================================================
PART 5: Can b1 <= 0?
======================================================================
  b1 = a1 - 2*a2
  b1 <= 0 iff a1 <= 2*a2
  This requires: # disjoint pairs >= (# total cycles)/2
  At n=5: a2=0, so b1 = a1 >= 0. b1=0 only for transitive.
  At n=7: need a1 <= 2*a2. Since a2 <= C(alpha_1 choose 2)...

  Checking b1 sign at n=9 (small sample):
